</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, I suppose.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>- There will now be a confirmation window available when spending AA points.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Now if there were only an option to refund AA spent on useless abilities, like <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Servant of Ro</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, even at a reduced rate <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(2 for 3, 3 for 5, etc.)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  Alternately, a button in the user interface which sends an electric shock for the designers and programmers responsible for those abilities.  No confirmation box needed for that.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>** NPCs **<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I don't know whether to be encouraged by the attention to detail or discouraged by the poor prioritization being demonstrated here.  Well, some important bugs have been fixed or at least announced as being fixed, so there is always hope.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>- Removed Sarnak Slaves from Nurga, since they had no models there to use and looked like the base model human (Doug).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Beware of Doug.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>But if they could make such a move, why could they not put some other uber rare spells on more boss mobs (like GSS for wizards)?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Much of wizards' legitimate grievance appears to be the rarity of key spells, especially when other classes' best nukes are more easily obtained.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>The Dweller In Darkness:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Can we make a formal petition about our bolts now?<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Edano:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  It's the most insignificant issue, and petitions do nothing anyway.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Got to disagree here with <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Edano</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> on both counts.<br>
<br>
First, since hitting with bolts depends on geometry, knowing their flight path can help a great deal in figuring out where best to cast them.  As bolts are also among are best bang per buck, or even our biggest bang, having the information to use them well strikes me as significant.  If it were a rain or something, graphics would not be important.<br>
<br>
Second, while <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Verant</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> officially ignores petitions, it is obvious that they respond to the player base.  What else do you recommend, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Edano</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, whining?  If you think of petitions as a formal complaint, and not some official process that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Verant</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is obligated to respond to, then petitions have their place.  My experience has been that focused, well supported petitions can produce results.  For example:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showMessage?topicID=90.topic">PETITION: Reduce Pet Penalties</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showMessage?topicID=97.topic">REQUEST: Reduce Pathing Costs</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showMessage?topicID=82.topic">Increased Pet Strength</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
As we all know, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The Great Patch</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> removed the pet experience penalty, made pets neutral faction, and made post-55 elemental stronger.<br>
<br>
I see a petition as a distillation of the will of a significant faction of the player community.  While formally <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Verant</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> cannot acknowledge petitions, the fact remains that they have been used to good effect in the past.<br>
